<br>
<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
Name the original authors, and year if known, and and use &#8216;as cited in&#8217; to refer to 
the secondary work you read. For example, a study by Jones and Chan was quoted in a work by Smith, 
but you did not read the study by Jones and Chan.
<br>
<br>
If the name of the original author is included in the sentence, the year of the original work, 
if known, and the name and date of the secondary source you read is provided in parentheses.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Webber and Reed (2010, as cited in Smith, 2017) indicated that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
Otherwise, the original authors and the secondary author and date should be included in parentheses.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	A recent study (Jones &amp; Chan, as cited in Smith, 2017) showed that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are using a direct quotation, consisting of fewer than 40 words, enclose the quote using 
double quotation marks and include page numbers.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	JWebber and Reed (2010, as cited in Smith, 2017) observed that &#34;chocolate has several 
	health benefits&#34; 
	(p. 56).
	<br>
	Alternatively: &#34;Chocolate has several health benefits&#34; (Jones &amp; Chan, as cited in 
	Smith, 2017, p. 56).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 40 words, the quote is displayed in a double spaced, indented 
block at 1.27cm from the left margin. Do not use double quotation marks to enclose a block quotation.
